1. ONE-PAGE DOCUMENT (Kubernetes Setup Summary)
🚀 Project: Spring Boot + PostgreSQL on Kubernetes
📌 Overview

Deployed a containerized Spring Boot application with PostgreSQL on Kubernetes using Docker Desktop. Enabled service-to-service communication and external access for testing.

🏗️ Architecture
Client → Service (NodePort / Port-forward)
           ↓
     Spring Boot Pods
           ↓
     PostgreSQL Service
           ↓
     PostgreSQL Pod
⚙️ Key Components
1. Deployment
Spring Boot (replicas = 2)
PostgreSQL (replicas = 1)
2. Services
springboot-service → NodePort (external access)
postgres → ClusterIP (internal only)
🔗 Networking
Internal DB connection:
jdbc:postgresql://postgres:5432/devdb
Port forwarding (local access):
kubectl port-forward service/postgres 5433:5432
kubectl port-forward service/springboot-service 8080:80
🌐 Access
API:
http://localhost:8080/users
PostgreSQL (pgAdmin):
Host: localhost
Port: 5433
User: devuser
Password: devpass
🔧 Commands Used
kubectl apply -f k8s/
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc
kubectl logs <pod>
kubectl port-forward service/<name> <local>:<container>
⚠️ Issues Faced & Fixes
Issue	Fix
Kubernetes not running	Enable in Docker Desktop
NodePort not accessible	Use port-forward
DB connection failed	Use service name (postgres)
Port conflict (5432)	Use 5433 via port-forward
🧠 Key Learnings
Kubernetes uses service names, not localhost
Pods are ephemeral (stateless by default)
Services enable internal communication
kubectl port-forward is essential for debugging
Docker Compose ≠ Kubernetes (different architecture)